Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and confirm:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and use `Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior` (toolbar back):

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    public EditProductPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Custom back button labeled "Cancel"
        Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior(this, new BackButtonBehavior
        {
            TextOverride = "Cancel",
            Command = new Command(async () => await ConfirmAndNavigateBack())
        });
    }

    // Handles Android/hardware back button
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () =>
                await ConfirmAndNavigateBack());
            return true; // cancel default navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async Task ConfirmAndNavigateBack()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!leave) return; // cancel navigation
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnBackButtonPressed`** — intercepts Android/hardware back. Return `true` to cancel.
- **`BackButtonBehavior`** — replaces the Shell toolbar back button. `TextOverride = "Cancel"` changes the label; `Command` routes through your confirmation logic.
- **`DisplayAlert`** — shows the confirmation dialog. Navigation only proceeds if the user taps "Discard".

Set `_hasUnsavedChanges = true` whenever your form fields change (e.g., via property setters or `TextChanged` events).
